41: Ali Boulala: A highly influential and legendary professional skateboarder who originates from Stockholm, Sweden. He gained significant international recognition in the late 1990s and early 2000s, most notably as a professional rider for Flip Skateboards. Boulala was celebrated for his incredibly fearless and often high-risk approach to skateboarding, pushing boundaries with massive gaps and daring stunts. His video parts, particularly his segment in the iconic "Baker 3" video, are considered classics within skateboarding culture. He also had a signature shoe with Circa Footwear.

Oskar Rozenberg Hallberg (Oski): An exceptionally talented and prominent professional skateboarder from Malmö, Sweden. Oski first turned professional for Polar Skate Co. and later joined the prestigious Nike SB team, a testament to his skill. He is widely acclaimed for his unique, powerful, and incredibly fluid style, especially when skating transition, bowls, and park terrain. Oski has achieved significant success in competitive skateboarding, including winning multiple Vans Park Series events, solidifying his status as one of the world's top park skaters.

Fernando Bramsmark: A distinguished professional skateboarder who hails from Malmö, Sweden, and is a key rider for Polar Skate Co. Bramsmark is widely recognized for his raw power, remarkable speed, and an aggressive yet controlled style that allows him to tackle large obstacles and diverse street terrains with confidence. His approach to skateboarding is often described as impactful and direct.

Josef Scott Jatta: A professional skateboarder from Malmö, Sweden, who also rides for Polar Skate Co. Josef is highly regarded for his exceptionally smooth, technical, and effortlessly stylish approach to street skateboarding. He has a knack for making complex tricks appear seamless and graceful, contributing to his distinctive and admired style within the skateboarding community.

Daniel Hakansson: A professional skateboarder from Sweden, known for his consistent presence and contributions to the European skateboarding scene. He is recognized for his versatile street skating abilities and has been featured in various skate videos and publications, showcasing his solid technical skills.

Jesper Lind: A professional skateboarder from Sweden, who has made a name for himself through his technical prowess and dedication to street skateboarding. He is a respected figure within the Swedish skateboarding community, known for his precise execution of tricks.

Micke Johansson: A veteran professional skateboarder from Sweden, Micke Johansson has been a significant and enduring figure in the Swedish skateboarding community for many years. He is known for his long-standing presence, consistent style, and contributions to the development of skateboarding in Sweden.

John Dahlquist: A professional skateboarder from Sweden, recognized for his strong street skating abilities and his active participation in the Swedish skateboarding landscape. He has been featured in various skate media, showcasing his skills.
Jonas Skrinnare: A professional skateboarder from Sweden, known for his contributions to the Swedish skateboarding scene and his solid performance in various skateboarding disciplines.

108: Nyårsdagen (New Year's Day) - January 1st - Public Holiday - This day marks the beginning of the Gregorian calendar year and is a nationwide public holiday in Sweden, observed with celebrations and often fireworks from the previous New Year's Eve.
Trettondagsafton (Epiphany Eve) - January 5th - Unofficial Holiday - While not a public holiday, many Swedes work a half-day or take the day off to prepare for Epiphany.

Trettondedag jul (Epiphany) - January 6th - Public Holiday - This Christian holiday commemorates the manifestation of God in human form in Jesus Christ, specifically the visit of the Magi to the Christ child. It is a public holiday across Sweden.

Långfredagen (Good Friday) - The Friday before Easter Sunday (date varies annually) - Public Holiday - This solemn Christian holiday commemorates the crucifixion of Jesus Christ. It is a public holiday throughout Sweden, and many businesses are closed.

Påskafton (Easter Eve) - The Saturday before Easter Sunday (date varies annually) - Unofficial Holiday - This day is a significant part of the Easter celebrations in Sweden, with many shops closing early. It is not a public holiday.

Påskdagen (Easter Sunday) - The first Sunday after the first full moon following the spring equinox (date varies annually) - Public Holiday - This is the central Christian holiday celebrating the resurrection of Jesus Christ. As it always falls on a Sunday, it does not typically grant an extra day off work, but it is officially recognized as a public holiday.

Annandag påsk (Easter Monday) - The Monday after Easter Sunday (date varies annually) - Public Holiday - This day follows Easter Sunday and is a public holiday in Sweden, providing an extended weekend for many.

Valborgsmässoafton (Walpurgis Night) - April 30th - Unofficial Holiday - This traditional spring festival is widely celebrated across Sweden with large bonfires, singing, and student festivities, particularly in university towns like Uppsala and Lund. It is not a public holiday.

Första maj (May Day / Labour Day) - May 1st - Public Holiday - This international holiday celebrates workers' rights and the labor movement. It is a public holiday in Sweden, often marked by political demonstrations and parades.

Kristi himmelsfärdsdag (Ascension Day) - 39 days after Easter Sunday (always a Thursday, date varies annually) - Public Holiday - This Christian holiday commemorates the ascension of Jesus Christ into heaven. It is a public holiday in Sweden, often creating a long weekend for those who take the Friday off.

Mors dag (Mother's Day) - Last Sunday in May (date varies annually) - Unofficial Holiday - This day is dedicated to celebrating mothers and motherhood, observed with gifts and family gatherings. It is not a public holiday.

Sveriges nationaldag (National Day of Sweden) - June 6th - Public Holiday - This day celebrates two significant historical events: the election of Gustav Vasa as king in 1523, which is considered the founding of modern Sweden, and the adoption of a new constitution in 1809. It became a public holiday in 2005.

Midsommarafton (Midsummer's Eve) - The Friday between June 19th and June 25th (date varies annually) - Unofficial Holiday - This is arguably the most important unofficial holiday in Sweden. While not a public holiday, it is widely treated as one, with many workplaces giving employees a half-day or full-day off. It is the main day for Midsummer celebrations, including dancing around the maypole, traditional food, and flower wreaths.

Midsommardagen (Midsummer's Day) - The Saturday between June 20th and June 26th (date varies annually) - Public Holiday - This holiday celebrates the summer solstice and is one of the most important cultural celebrations in Sweden. As it always falls on a Saturday, it does not typically grant an extra day off work, but it is officially recognized as a public holiday.

Alla helgons dag (All Saints' Day) - The first Saturday in November (date varies annually) - Public Holiday - This Christian holiday commemorates all Christian saints, known and unknown. It is a public holiday in Sweden. As it always falls on a Saturday, it does not typically grant an extra day off work. The preceding day, Alla helgons afton (All Saints' Eve), is often a half-day off for many.

Fars dag (Father's Day) - Second Sunday in November (date varies annually) - Unofficial Holiday - This day is dedicated to celebrating fathers and fatherhood, observed with gifts and family gatherings. It is not a public holiday.

Lucia (Saint Lucy's Day) - December 13th - Unofficial Holiday - This is a major cultural celebration of light, particularly important in schools, churches, and workplaces. It involves processions with a "Lucia" wearing a crown of candles and singing traditional songs. It is not a public holiday.

Julafton (Christmas Eve) - December 24th - Unofficial Holiday - This is the main day of Christmas celebration in Sweden, with gift-giving, traditional Christmas dinner (julbord), and family gatherings. While not a public holiday, most people are off work or take the day off.

Juldagen (Christmas Day) - December 25th - Public Holiday - This Christian holiday celebrates the birth of Jesus Christ. It is a major public holiday in Sweden, following the main Christmas celebrations on Christmas Eve.
Annandag jul (Boxing Day / Saint Stephen's Day) - December 26th - Public Holiday - This day follows Christmas Day and is a public holiday in Sweden, extending the Christmas break for many.

Nyårsafton (New Year's Eve) - December 31st - Unofficial Holiday - This day is celebrated with parties, fireworks, and countdowns to the new year. While not a public holiday, many people are off work or take the day off.

Regional Holidays - No Specific Official Days - Sweden does not have specific "regional holidays" that are official days off work and apply only to certain parts of the country. All public holidays are national. While local traditions and celebrations might be more prominent in specific regions for certain days, these do not constitute official regional holidays with time off work.
